			"person": "Frau Prof. in Annette Stahmer, Herr Prof. André Heers",
			"titel": "International Workshop: Text, Sound, Typography / Alessandro Bosetti",
			"rythmus": "Beginn",
			"zeit": "03.12.2012 - 10:00 Uhr",
			"beginn": "07.12.2012 - 17:00 Uhr",
			"typ": "Workshop",
			"modul": "KoDe M.A. Studienmodul 2, 1. Semester",
			"details": "Sound artist and composer Alessandro Bosetti works on the ephemeral language and voice particles within the context of musical composition. Those particles originate from field researches, conversations, casual interactions, rumors, misunderstandings and incomplete translations. His notion of text within music is fluid, variable and swarming and resists definitive postures and compilations along the language vs. music continuum. He will offer a collaborative workshop exploring typographic possibilities within text sound compositions and ways to make such a mutable material visible while positioning it on the page or the screen. \n\nAlessandro Bosetti is an Italian composer, sound artist and performer born in 1973. He's main focus is in the fringe area between spoken language and music. He created a series of highly compelling sound works where relational aesthetics meets innovative composition and published more than a dozen of cd's of his own music along with countless other collaborations. Since 2000 he has been a key Ars Acustica figure, and created a vast body of electro acoustic and text sound works for institutions as WDR Studio Akustische Kunst, DeutschlandRadio and GRM among many other. Pieces like Il Fiore della Bocca (Rossbin/DLR 2005) – a work on the vocality of the mentally and physically impaired – and African Feedback – a collaborative scrutiny on experimental music in West Africa – (Errant Bodies Press, 2004) have received wide recognition. Alessandro Bosetti is an emotional performer that has consistently toured in Europe, Asia and the United States as a soloist, leading his speech ensemble Trophies with Tony Buck and Kenta Nagai and in collaborations with fellow vocal performers as Jennifer Walshe and Tomomi Adachi and with pianist Chris Abrahams."
